literature a real shot.

100
00:08:27,390 --> 00:08:30,600
- Until now.
- Please...Gil...

101
00:08:30,600 --> 00:08:34,060
Honey, just promise me something.

102
00:08:34,180 --> 00:08:36,780
If this book...doesn't pan out,

103
00:08:36,840 --> 00:08:39,050
that you'll stop
eating your brains out,

104
00:08:39,050 --> 00:08:42,030
and just go back to doing
what you do best.

105
00:08:42,140 --> 00:08:46,850
I mean, the studios adore you.
You're in demand...

106
00:08:46,900 --> 00:08:50,380
Do you really want to give
it all up just to struggle?

107
00:08:50,420 --> 00:08:53,470
- Well...
- Mmm?

108
00:08:55,080 --> 00:08:56,320
Mmm?

109
00:08:57,200 --> 00:09:00,030
Why would you...want to do that?

110
00:09:00,170 --> 00:09:02,370
I believe Louis moved his court here,

111
00:09:02,370 --> 00:09:04,710
uh, in 1682.

112
00:09:04,870 --> 00:09:06,800
Originally, all this was swampland.

113
00:09:06,810 --> 00:09:08,680
In fact, if I'm not mistaken,

114
00:09:08,740 --> 00:09:12,010
uh... in Old French, the word "versailles"

115
00:09:12,150 --> 00:09:14,300
means, uh, something like,

116
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:17,670
- "terrain were the weeds have been pulled."
- Is that right?

117
00:09:17,760 --> 00:09:20,380
Uh... The... uh, middle section here

118
00:09:20,390 --> 00:09:24,270
uh... is... uh, French classical style at its height.

119
00:09:24,270 --> 00:09:27,400
Uh... The work, I believe, of...
uh, "Louis Vau" (Louis le Vau)

120
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:29,260
- Yes.
- Uh...Mansart...I think...

121
00:09:29,260 --> 00:09:31,560
- Manzard. (sic.)
- ...and Charles le Brun, I believe.

122
00:09:31,560 --> 00:09:32,570
Yes, that's right.

123
00:09:32,590 --> 00:09:34,690
I could get used to a summer home like this.

124
00:09:34,690 --> 00:09:36,610
- I know you could.
- Me, too,

125
00:09:36,610 --> 00:09:38,780
except, remember: in those days,

126
00:09:38,780 --> 00:09:40,870
they only had baths,
and I'm definitely a shower man.

127
00:09:40,870 --> 00:09:43,660
Where are you two planning on
moving after you get married?

128
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:45,960
Uh...Malibu.

129
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:47,630
- Really?
- We're thinking about Malibu, yeah.

130
00:09:47,630 --> 00:09:50,900
I'm pushing for a little
attic in Paris with a skylight.

131
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:52,490
- La bowhem? (sic.)
- Yeah,

132
00:09:52,490 --> 00:09:54,210
all that's missing is the tuberculosis.

133
00:09:54,300 --> 00:09:55,790
Exactly. Thank you.

134
00:09:55,930 --> 00:09:58,680
I mean, you know, the problem
is that he's not exactly sure

135
00:09:58,680 --> 00:10:00,680
- he can write a novel.
- Really?

136
00:10:00,680 --> 00:10:04,380
- Well...
- I mean, honey, so far your track record's-- you know, and...

137
00:10:04,470 --> 00:10:06,770
well, everyone loves your movies.

138
00:10:06,890 --> 00:10:09,340
- Yeah, well scripts are easier, so...
- Wow.

139
00:10:09,430 --> 00:10:12,020
Why don't you tell them about the lead
character that you're working on right now?

140
00:10:12,020 --> 00:10:13,890
- Yes!  - Oh, come on.
- I don't like to discuss my work.

141
00:10:13,890 --> 00:10:17,590
Well, dear, you don't have to tell
them the whole plot, just the character.

142
00:10:17,630 --> 00:10:19,580
- No, no, no.
- Okay.

143
00:10:19,580 --> 00:10:21,320
He works in a nostalgia shop.

144
00:10:21,320 --> 00:10:24,690
- What's a-- What's a nostalgia shop?
- Oh, not one of those stores where they sell

145
00:10:24,690 --> 00:10:27,300
Shirley Temple dolls and old radios?

146
00:10:27,300 --> 00:10:29,270
- And I never know who buys that stuff. Who'd want it?
- Exactly.

147
00:10:29,300 --> 00:10:32,630
- I don't know.
- Well, people who live in the past,

148
00:10:32,650 --> 00:10:35,490
people who think that
their lives would be happier

149
00:10:35,610 --> 00:10:37,880
if they lived in an earlier time.

150
00:10:37,910 --> 00:10:39,580
And just which era

151
00:10:39,580 --> 00:10:42,890
would you have preferred
to live in, Miniver Cheevy?

152
00:10:42,990 --> 00:10:45,990
Paris in the '20s, in the rain.

153
00:10:46,090 --> 00:10:47,860
- Wouldn't have been bad.
- And the rain was an acid rain.

154
00:10:47,860 --> 00:10:49,870
Oh, I see! And no global warming,

155
00:10:49,930 --> 00:10:51,950
no TV and suicide bombing,

156
00:10:51,950 --> 00:10:54,050
and nuclear weapons, drug cartels!

157
00:10:54,050 --> 00:10:56,760
Usual menu of clichéd horror stories.

158
00:10:56,760 --> 00:10:58,880
You know, nostalgia is denial.

159
00:10:58,900 --> 00:11:02,270
- Denial of the painful present.
- Oh, whoa!

160
00:11:02,290 --> 00:11:05,080
Gil is a complete romantic.
I mean, he would be

161
00:11:05,190 --> 00:11:08,170
more than happy living in a
complete state of perpetual denial.

162
00:11:08,170 --> 00:11:10,370
- Really?
- And the name for this fallacy

163
00:11:10,370 --> 00:11:13,740
is called "golden-age thinking."

164
00:11:13,770 --> 00:11:16,440
- Touché.
- Yeah, the erroneous notion that

165
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:19,890
a different time period is better
than the one one's living in.

166
00:11:19,890 --> 00:11:23,720
It's a flaw in the Romantic
imagination of those people who...

167
00:11:23,740 --> 00:11:27,930
who find it difficult to
cope with the depressive.

168
00:11:28,800 --> 00:11:31,230
<i>- Yes.
- This is the nicest ring we saw.</i>

169
00:11:31,230 --> 00:11:33,740
Diamonds for a wedding band.

170
00:11:33,750 --> 00:11:36,330
That's the way you'd have to go.
And then, everyone will see

171
00:11:36,350 --> 00:11:38,900
it in the back row when
he puts it on my finger.

172
00:11:38,930 --> 00:11:42,950
Oh, Inez. It's gonna be such an event!

173
00:11:44,090 --> 00:11:47,160
- I only wish that...
- I don't want to keep going over it.

174
00:11:47,200 --> 00:11:50,280
It's your choice. What can I say?

175
00:11:50,410 --> 00:11:54,930
Gil is-- he's smart,
and he's very successful.

176
00:11:54,940 --> 00:11:58,790
- He talks about giving that all up and moving here!
- Oh, yeah, he TALKS about it.

177
00:11:58,910 --> 00:12:01,300
Well, that frightens me.

178
00:12:01,750 --> 00:12:04,950
This is, of course, Rodin's most famous statue.

179
00:12:04,970 --> 00:12:08,380
