00:30:37,860 --> 00:30:41,930
- She's right, Gil.
- I know, but we haven't even found a house yet,

454
00:30:41,930 --> 00:30:46,850
and we're trying to keep expenses down,
so I don't have to take any crummy rewrite jobs.

455
00:30:46,850 --> 00:30:49,130
Well, you get what you pay for.

456
00:30:49,130 --> 00:30:51,610
- Nice.
- Cheap is cheap.

457
00:30:53,220 --> 00:30:55,310
OK, you guys want to walk back?

458
00:30:55,310 --> 00:30:57,910
Walk? No, it's starting to rain.

459
00:30:58,080 --> 00:31:00,930
Oh, it'll be nice walking in the rain!
It's beautiful!

460
00:31:00,930 --> 00:31:04,290
No, there's nothing beautiful
about walking in the rain.

461
00:31:04,290 --> 00:31:06,870
No, don't forget.
We're taking you to dinner tonight.

462
00:31:06,870 --> 00:31:08,310
Oh, right. Yes. Great.

463
00:31:08,310 --> 00:31:12,480
And then, also, I have a big
surprise for you after dinner.

464
00:31:12,480 --> 00:31:17,020
- What? No. I don't like surprises.
- I have an incredible...Trust me, you're gonna love this.

465
00:31:17,020 --> 00:31:18,890
- What is it?
- Are you sure you don't want to walk in the rain?

466
00:31:18,890 --> 00:31:23,220
This is our last chance.
It's not that bad out.

467
00:31:23,700 --> 00:31:25,220
Okay.

468
00:31:28,530 --> 00:31:30,960
I don't understand.
Where are we going?

469
00:31:30,960 --> 00:31:32,960
But, you made us rush through dinner,

470
00:31:32,960 --> 00:31:35,440
and Dad wasn't finished with his profiteroles.

471
00:31:35,440 --> 00:31:40,040
Profiteroles? You're going to have
the most amazing adventure of your life!

472
00:31:40,040 --> 00:31:43,700
- Where?
- Just, Inez, please.

473
00:31:44,060 --> 00:31:48,350
- Why are you carrying that manuscript around?
- You'll see, and when you do,

474
00:31:48,350 --> 00:31:50,350
your jaw is gonna drop.

475
00:31:50,350 --> 00:31:55,770
OK. You know I wouldn't hide anything,
so if I'm saying it's incredible,

476
00:31:55,770 --> 00:31:59,530
- it's...
- OK.

477
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:07,690
- It's just, I don't understand!
- I know. You've been wondering why I've been acting strange all day?

478
00:32:07,690 --> 00:32:09,960
- Yeah.
- Well, you're about to find out,

479
00:32:09,960 --> 00:32:14,800
and you're gonna wonder why I wasn't
acting more strange, when you find out.

480
00:32:14,800 --> 00:32:17,300
- This is very...
- I know. I know.

481
00:32:27,050 --> 00:32:30,830
Well, I don't know what you're carrying on about,
but this is not my idea of an amazing adventure.

482
00:32:30,830 --> 00:32:34,350
I am tired from the gym and a massage,
so I'm gonna get this cab.

483
00:32:34,350 --> 00:32:36,830
- Taxi!
- Inez, wait!

484
00:32:36,830 --> 00:32:38,960
- Let's just wait a little longer.
- Look,

485
00:32:39,230 --> 00:32:42,450
you want to walk the streets of Paris,
and take it in by night,

486
00:32:42,450 --> 00:32:46,270
that's fine. You go ahead.
But I'm in the middle of a great book that Carol lent me.

487
00:32:46,270 --> 00:32:49,130
Come on, just 10 more minutes,
and then we can walk home.

488
00:32:49,130 --> 00:32:52,450
If I'm asleep when you get in,
don't wake me up.

489
00:32:57,870 --> 00:33:00,600
What am I doing wrong?

490
00:33:00,600 --> 00:33:04,070
Unless she's right,
and I need to see a neurologist.

491
00:33:04,380 --> 00:33:09,430
OK, you left the wine-tasting, a little drunk,
but not out of control.

492
00:33:09,430 --> 00:33:13,230
Lost, you walk along...
this is the spot...

493
00:33:13,230 --> 00:33:15,840
I mean, it's just like a one-shot deal.

494
00:33:17,760 --> 00:33:20,570
The clock struck midnight...

495
00:33:34,400 --> 00:33:35,940
Hello!

496
00:33:38,880 --> 00:33:41,680
Oh, hi, Mr. Hemingway. Here.

497
00:33:41,680 --> 00:33:43,680
Let me just jump in.

498
00:33:52,510 --> 00:33:55,570
The assignment was to take the hill.
There were 4 of us.

499
00:33:55,570 --> 00:33:59,030
5 if you counted Vicente, but he had
lost his hand when a grenade went off

500
00:33:59,030 --> 00:34:01,510
and couldn't fight as he could when I first met him.

501
00:34:01,510 --> 00:34:03,510
And he was young, and brave.

502
00:34:03,510 --> 00:34:07,680
And the hill was soggy from days of rain,
and the hill sloped down toward a road,

503
00:34:07,680 --> 00:34:10,160
and there were many German soldiers on the road.

504
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:12,270
And the idea was to aim for the first group,

505
00:34:12,270 --> 00:34:15,430
and if our aim was true, we could delay them.

506
00:34:15,930 --> 00:34:18,380
- Were you scared?
- Of what?

507
00:34:19,460 --> 00:34:21,100
Getting killed?

508
00:34:21,930 --> 00:34:24,650
You'll never write well
if you're afraid of dying.

509
00:34:24,770 --> 00:34:27,360
- Do you?
- Yeah, I do. I'd say it's probably...

510
00:34:27,360 --> 00:34:29,530
maybe my greatest fear, actually.

511
00:34:29,530 --> 00:34:33,120
Well, that's something all men before
you have done. All men will do.

512
00:34:33,120 --> 00:34:37,130
- I know. I know.
- Have you ever made love to a truly great woman?

513
00:34:37,330 --> 00:34:40,580
Actually, my fiancée is pretty sexy.

514
00:34:40,580 --> 00:34:43,550
And when you make love to her,
you feel true, and beautiful

515
00:34:43,550 --> 00:34:47,720
passion, and you, for at least that moment,
lose your fear of death.

516
00:34:47,720 --> 00:34:50,000
No. That doesn't happen.

517
00:34:50,220 --> 00:34:54,000
I believe that love that is true and real
creates a respite from death.

518
00:34:54,000 --> 00:34:58,570
All cowardice comes from not loving,
or not loving well, which is the same thing.

519
00:34:58,570 --> 00:35:02,540
And when the man who is brave and true
looks Death squarely in the face

520
00:35:02,540 --> 00:35:06,920
like some rhino-hunters I know,
or Belmonte, who's truly brave.

521
00:35:06,920 --> 00:35:12,050
It is because they love with sufficient
passion, to push death out of their minds,

522
00:35:12,050 --> 00:35:14,920
until it returns, as it does, to all men.

523
00:35:15,240 --> 00:35:18,140
And then you must make really good love again.

524
00:35:19,630 --> 00:35:21,480
Think about it.

525
00:35:36,400 --> 00:35:37,750
- Alice. How the hell are you?
- Hi!

526
00:35:37,750 --> 00:35:40,980
Good? Good. Ah, she's here. Follow me.

527
00:35:41,100 --> 00:35:43,550
- <i>Non. Je ne suis pas d'accord.</i>(No. I don't agree.)
- <i>Mais pourquoi</i>? (But why?)

528
00:35:43,550 --> 00:35:44,880
<i>Parce-que</i>... (Because...)

529
00:35:44,880 --> 00:35:47,370
This is Gil Pender, Miss Stein.

530
00:35:47,370 --> 00:35:49,940
He's a young American writer.
I thought you two should know each other.

531
00:35:49,940 --> 00:35:51,420
I'm glad you're here.

532
00:35:51,420 --> 00:35:54,440
You can help decide which of us is right,
and which of us is wrong.

533
00:35:54,440 --> 00:35:57,840
I was just telling Pablo that
this portrait doesn't capture Adriana.

534
00:35:57,840 --> 00:36:01,120
It has a universality, but no objectivity.

535
00:36:01,120 --> 00:36:03,380
<i>Non, non, non. Vous ne le comprenez pas correctement.</i>
(No, no ,no. You don't understand correctly.)

536
00:36:03,380 --> 00:36:05,110
<i>Connaisez pas Adriana. Regardez...</i>
(You don't know Adriana. Look...)

537
00:36:05,110 --> 00:36:06,630
<i>Regardez le mouvement, le tableau.</i>
(Look at the motion, the painting.)

538
00:36:06,630 --> 00:36:08,390
<i>C'est exactement ce qu'elle représente!</i>
(It's exactly what she represents!)

539
00:36:08,420 --> 00:36:11,430
<i>Non. Tu n'as pas raison.</i>(No. You're wrong.)
Look how he's done her:

540
00:36:11,430 --> 00:36:13,820
dripping with sexual innuendo,

541
00:36:13,820 --> 00:36:17,880
carnal to the point of smoldering,
and, yes, she's beautiful, but

542
00:36:17,880 --> 00:36:20,840
it's a subtle beauty;
an implied sensuality.

543
00:36:20,970 --> 00:36:24,550
I mean, what is your first
impression of Adriana?

544
00:36:27,320 --> 00:36:29,120
Exceptionally lovely.

545
00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:32,450
<i>Belle, mais trop subtile. Plus implicite</i>, Pablo!
(Beautiful, but too subtle. More defined, Pablo!)

546
00:36:32,450 --> 00:36:34,830
Yes, you're right, Miss Stein.
'Course...uh...

547
00:36:34,880 --> 00:36:37,120
you can see why he's lost all objectivity.

548
00:36:37,120 --> 00:36:39,180
He's made a creature of Place Pigalle.

549
00:36:39,180 --> 00:36:40,900
A whore with volcanic appetites.

550
00:36:40,900 --> 00:36:43,470
<i>Non, non! C'est ce qu'elle vraiment si vous la connaissez!</i>
(No, no! It's true if you know her!)

551
00:36:43,470 --> 00:36:45,620
Yes, <i>avec toi, au privé</i>,
(Yes, with you, in private,)

552
00:36:45,640 --> 00:36:48,570
because she's your lover,
but we don't know her that way!

553
00:36:48,570 --> 00:36:52,490
So you make a petit-bourgeois judgment
and turn her into an object of pleasure.

554
00:36:52,490 --> 00:36:56,490
- It's more like a still-life than a portrait.
- <i>Non.</i>

555
00:36:56,490 --> 00:37:00,190
<i>Non. Non. Je ne suis pas d'accord.</i>
(No. No. I do not agree.)

556
00:37:00,380 --> 00:37:02,330
And what's this book of
yours I've been hearing about?

557
00:37:02,330 --> 00:37:03,390
Is this it?

558
00:37:03,390 --> 00:37:05,270
- Yeah, this is...uh...
- I'll take a look.

559
00:37:05,270 --> 00:37:07,090
Have you read it, Hemingway?

560
00:37:07,090 --> 00:37:10,710
No, this I leave to you.
You've always been a fine judge of my work.

561
00:37:10,940 --> 00:37:13,530
" "Out of the Past" was the name of the store,"

562
00:37:13,530 --> 00:37:15,960
"and its products consisted of memories."

563
00:37:15,960 --> 00:37:19,260
"What was prosaic and
even vulgar to one generation,"

564
00:37:19,260 --> 00:37:22,350
"had been transmuted by
the mere passing of years"

565
00:37:22,350 --> 00:37:26,600
"to a status at once magical and also camp."

566
00:37:26,760 --> 00:37:28,780
I love it.

567
00:37:29,230 --> 00:37:32,370
I'm already hooked.
Hooked!

568
00:37:33,230 --> 00:37:34,840
I'll start it tonight,

569
00:37:34,840 --> 00:37:37,760
but first, you and I
have something to talk about.

570
00:37:37,760 --> 00:37:41,350
<i>I've been waiting for two months
for a reply from that editor.</i>

571
00:37:41,350 --> 00:37:44,410
<i>I sent him the piece you and I
looked at, plus four others,</i>

572
00:37:44,410 --> 00:37:48,180
<i>plus four shorter pieces.
And this guy, I gave him a copy of the...</i>

573
00:37:50,670 --> 00:37:55,190
<i>- Nevertheless, two months: nary a word.
- Right.</i>

574
00:37:57,790 --> 00:38:01,180
So were you really hooked
with those opening lines?

575
00:38:02,310 --> 00:38:07,200
Oh, the past has always had a
great charisma for me.

576
00:38:07,200 --> 00:38:11,590
Oh, me, too.
Great charisma for me.

577
00:38:11,590 --> 00:38:14,410
I always say that I was born too late.

578
00:38:14,410 --> 00:38:17,150
<i>Mmm. Moi aussi.</i>
(Mmm. Me, too.)

579
00:38:17,520 --> 00:38:20,530
For me, <i>la Belle Époque Paris</i>
would have been perfect.

580
00:38:20,610 --> 00:38:23,660
- Really? Better than now?
- Yes.

581
00:38:23,670 --> 00:38:28,270
Another whole sensibility,
the street lamps, the kiosques,

582
00:38:28,270 --> 00:38:32,590
the...horse and carriages,

583
00:38:32,610 --> 00:38:35,380
and Maxim's then.

584
00:38:35,480 --> 00:38:37,960
You speak very good English.

585
00:38:38,200 --> 00:38:41,540
- No, not really.
- No, you do!

586
00:38:41,680 --> 00:38:44,000
How long have you been dating Picasso?

587
00:38:44,050 --> 00:38:47,020
My God, did I just say that?

588
00:38:47,140 --> 00:38:48,540
Pardon?

589
00:38:48,550 --> 00:38:54,690
I don't mean to...I didn't mean to pry....
Were you born in Paris?

590
00:38:55,160 --> 00:38:58,110
I was born in Bordeaux.

591
00:38:58,450 --> 00:39:01,240
I moved here to study fashion.

592
00:39:01,290 --> 00:39:03,100
But you don't want to hear all this.

593
00:39:03,100 --> 00:39:05,100
Yes, I do.

594
00:39:05,100 --> 00:39:09,700
Yes, continue.
You moved here to study fashion...

595
00:39:09,900 --> 00:39:14,140
I...came here to study with Coco Chanel,

596
00:39:14,180 --> 00:39:16,840
and I fell in love with <i>Paris</i>,

597
00:39:16,900 --> 00:39:18,910
and also,

598
00:39:19,030 --> 00:39:24,600
a very dark-eyed, haunted
Jewish-Italian painter.

599
00:39:25,790 --> 00:39:33,290
And I knew Amedeo had another woman, but still,
I couldn't resist moving into his apartment when he asked,

600
00:39:33,290 --> 00:39:36,080
and it was a beautiful six months.

601
00:39:36,130 --> 00:39:39,210
M..M...Modigliani?

602
00:39:39,210 --> 00:39:43,710
You lived with...
You lived with Modigliani?

603
00:39:43,710 --> 00:39:48,750
You asked me,
so I'm telling you my sad story.

604
00:39:50,230 --> 00:39:53,740
With Braque, though, there was another woman.

605
00:39:54,570 --> 00:39:56,180
Many.

606
00:39:56,990 --> 00:39:58,940
And now,

607
00:39:58,940 --> 00:40:00,940
with Pablo.

608
00:40:00,940 --> 00:40:04,700
I mean, he's married,
but...

609
00:40:04,890 --> 00:40:08,340
every day, it's on-again, off-again.

610
00:40:08,340 --> 00:40:13,590
I don't know how any woman
can stay with him. He's so difficult.

611
00:40:14,710 --> 00:40:19,030
My God, you take "art groupie"
to a whole new level!

612
00:40:19,030 --> 00:40:23,300
- Pardon?
- Nothing. I was just saying that...

613
00:40:23,300 --> 00:40:25,300
But tell me about yourself.

614
00:40:25,300 --> 00:40:30,360
- What? Well, what can I say...
- So, have you come to Paris to write?

615
00:40:30,640 --> 00:40:32,840
Because, you know,

616
00:40:32,840 --> 00:40:37,840
these days, so many Americans
feel the need to move here.

617
00:40:39,670 --> 00:40:42,480
Isn't Hemingway attractive?

618
00:40:42,570 --> 00:40:45,480
I love his writing.

619
00:40:45,940 --> 00:40:49,180
I know. Actually, I'm just here visiting.

620
00:40:49,180 --> 00:40:51,180
Oh, you must stay here.

621
00:40:51,180 --> 00:40:55,480
- Really?
- Yeah. It's a wonderful city, for

622
00:40:55,480 --> 00:41:00,980
- writers, artists.
- I know. I'd like to, but it's not that easy.

623
00:41:01,400 --> 00:41:02,980
And,

624
00:41:03,910 --> 00:41:07,960
I didn't fall in love madly with your book...

625
00:41:07,960 --> 00:41:10,660
- Really?
- ...so I want to hear the rest of it.

626
00:41:10,750 --> 00:41:15,390
- You really like? Because I'm still kind of tinkering...
- Pender?

627
00:41:15,390 --> 00:41:19,770
- Yeah, let's go up to Montmartre. Let's get a drink, OK?
- Uh...yeah.

628
00:41:19,770 --> 00:41:24,200
I'll discuss your book with you as soon as I've finished it.
Where can I reach you?

629
00:41:24,200 --> 00:41:28,580
Why don't I drop back by, instead of you
trying to find me, if that's all right?

630
00:41:28,580 --> 00:41:32,910
- We run an open house.
- Are you coming with us?

631
00:41:32,940 --> 00:41:36,580
I wish that I could.
I cant, but

632
00:41:36,580 --> 00:41:39,540
hopefully I'll see you again eventually.

633
00:41:39,540 --> 00:41:41,750
That would be nice.

634
00:41:41,960 --> 00:41:45,020
- Let's go!
- One of these days, I plan to steal you away from this genius

635
00:41:45,020 --> 00:41:47,650
who's great, but he's no Miró.

636
00:42:04,670 --> 00:42:06,750
I'm Gil Pender.

637
00:42:06,750 --> 00:42:11,010
I was with Hemingway, and Picasso.

638
00:42:11,010 --> 00:42:15,330
Pablo Picasso, and Ernest Hemingway.

639
00:42:16,160 --> 00:42:19,720
I'm Gil Pender, from Pasadena!

640
00:42:20,230 --> 00:42:24,310
Cub Scouts. I failed freshman English.

641
00:42:24,750 --> 00:42:28,120
Little old Gil Pender has his novel

642
00:42:28,120 --> 00:42:31,860
with Gertrude. Stein.

643
00:42:32,330 --> 00:42:35,300
Boy, that girl was so...

644
00:42:35,770 --> 00:42:38,000
lovely.

645
00:42:41,140 --> 00:42:44,340
Well, it's a shame you two didn't
come to the movies with us last night,

646
00:42:44,360 --> 00:42:47,270
We saw a wonderfully
funny American film.

647
00:42:47,270 --> 00:42:48,960
Who was in it?

648
00:42:48,960 --> 00:42:50,800
Oh, I don't know.
I forget the name.

649
00:42:50,800 --> 00:42:54,500
Wonderful but forgettable.
That sounds like a picture I've seen.

650
00:42:54,500 --> 00:42:56,190
I probably wrote it.

651
00:42:56,190 --> 00:42:59,020
Well, I know it was moronic and infantile, and

652
00:42:59,020 --> 00:43:01,850
utterly lacking in any wit or believability,

653
00:43:01,850 --> 00:43:05,280
- but John and I laughed in spite of all that.
- Have we been down this way yet?

654
00:43:05,280 --> 00:43:07,220
Was it?

655
00:43:08,450 --> 00:43:10,210
What time did you get in last night?

656
00:43:10,210 --> 00:43:13,030
Not that late...uh...
I was...uh...

657
00:43:13,030 --> 00:43:16,520
I'm really finding these midnight strolls
great for me creatively,

658
00:43:16,520 --> 00:43:19,740
without the distractions of the day.
I'll probably end up going on another little

659
00:43:19,740 --> 00:43:22,940
- hike tonight.
- Well, we'll see.

660
00:43:23,010 --> 00:43:25,480
Yeah. We'll see.

661
00:43:25,750 --> 00:43:29,140
Oh, look at those wonderful glass figures.

662
00:43:29,140 --> 00:43:34,160
[Cole Porter's "You Do Something to Me"]
♪ <i>...that simply mystifies me</i> ♪

663
00:43:34,360 --> 00:43:40,260
♪ <i>Tell me why should it be </i> ♪

664
00:43:40,640 --> 00:43:46,720
♪ <i>You have the power to hypnotize me</i> ♪

665
00:43:46,880 --> 00:43:48,540
<i>Vous aimez</i>?
(You like?)

666
00:43:48,650 --> 00:43:50,720
Yes. Very beautiful.

667
00:43:50,720 --> 00:43:52,810
- Oh. You're American.
- Yeah.

668
00:43:53,470 --> 00:43:54,960
You like Cole Porter?

669
00:43:54,960 --> 00:43:58,060
I do. I'm a big fan.
I like to

670
00:43:58,060 --> 00:44:02,180
kind of think I'm a member
of Linda and Cole's inner circle.

671
00:44:02,180 --> 00:44:04,180
I'm kidding.

672
00:44:05,070 --> 00:44:06,720
Very pretty lyrics.

673
00:44:06,720 --> 00:44:09,740
- Very amusing.
- Charming.

674
00:44:14,610 --> 00:44:16,450
Gil?

675
00:44:16,450 --> 00:44:18,910
- Gil? Hi.
- Yeah? Yes.

676
00:44:18,910 --> 00:44:21,370
- Yeah. We should go.
- We're going now?

677
00:44:21,370 --> 00:44:24,810
Yeah. We're meeting Paul and Carol
at the museum for the private showing.

678
00:44:24,810 --> 00:44:26,390
- OK. Yeah. Right.

679
00:44:26,400 --> 00:44:28,900
You know, Paul happens to be an expert in Monet,

680
00:44:28,900 --> 00:44:30,900
so you'll find it enlightening, I think.

681
00:44:30,900 --> 00:44:32,190
Yeah. OK.

682
00:44:32,190 --> 00:44:35,060
Let's get some culture.

683
00:44:36,010 --> 00:44:38,760
The juxtaposition of color is amazing.

684
00:44:38,760 --> 00:44:41,360
This man was the real father

685
00:44:41,360 --> 00:44:43,310
of abstract expressionism.

686
00:44:43,310 --> 00:44:45,570
I take that back.
Maybe Turner.

687
00:44:46,440 --> 00:44:48,510
I mean, I love Turner,

688
00:44:48,510 --> 00:44:50,510
but, I just find this...

689
00:44:50,510 --> 00:44:51,760
overwhelming.

690
00:44:51,760 --> 00:44:55,020
If I'm not mistaken,
it took him 2 years to complete this.

691
00:44:55,020 --> 00:44:58,230
He worked out of Giverny,
where he was frequently...

692
00:44:58,230 --> 00:45:01,480
I heard that Monet,
one of the things that he used to try to...

693
00:45:01,510 --> 00:45:04,140
Shh! I'm trying to hear Paul say it.

694
00:45:04,280 --> 00:45:06,440
Well, he was frequently
visited by Caillebotte,

695
00:45:06,440 --> 00:45:09,590
an artist who I personally feel was underrated.

696
00:45:09,990 --> 00:45:11,850
Ah. Now.

697
00:45:11,850 --> 00:45:14,190
Here's a superb Picasso.

698
00:45:14,190 --> 00:45:18,320
If I'm not mistaken, he painted
this marvelous portrait of his

699
00:45:18,320 --> 00:45:22,030
French mistress
Madeleine Brissou in the '20s.

700
00:45:22,490 --> 00:45:25,480
Paul, I'm gonna have to
differ with you on this one.

701
00:45:25,480 --> 00:45:27,770
- Really.
- Gil, just pay attention.

702
00:45:27,770 --> 00:45:29,370
You might learn something.

703
00:45:29,370 --> 00:45:31,480
OK, well, if I'm not mistaken,

704
00:45:31,480 --> 00:45:34,000
this was a failed attempt to capture

705
00:45:34,000 --> 00:45:36,810
a young French girl named Adriana,

706
00:45:36,810 --> 00:45:39,970
from Bordeaux, if my art history serves me,

707
00:45:39,970 --> 00:45:44,060
who came to Paris to study
costume design for the theater.

708
00:45:44,060 --> 00:45:47,990
I'm pretty sure she had an affair
with Modigliani, then Braque,

709
00:45:47,990 --> 00:45:50,650
which is how Pablo met her.
Picasso.

710
00:45:50,920 --> 00:45:52,730
Of course, what you don't get

711
00:45:52,730 --> 00:45:55,500
from this portrait
is the subtlety,

712
00:45:55,500 --> 00:45:58,020
and her beauty.
She was just a knock-out.

713
00:45:59,740 --> 00:46:01,980
What have you been smoking?

714
00:46:02,250 --> 00:46:04,890
I'd hardly call this picture marvelous,

715
00:46:04,890 --> 00:46:07,100
it's more of a petit-bourgeois statement

716
00:46:07,110 --> 00:46:10,110
on how Pablo sees her. Saw her.

717
00:46:10,390 --> 00:46:12,760
He's distracted by the fact
that she was a

718
00:46:12,760 --> 00:46:15,690
absolute volcano in the sack.

719
00:46:22,500 --> 00:46:24,510
Too rich for me.

720
00:46:25,820 --> 00:46:27,580
Where'd Gil run off to?

721
00:46:28,860 --> 00:46:30,240
Work.

722
00:46:31,620 --> 00:46:33,780
Been walking around Paris. You know,

723
00:46:33,780 --> 00:46:38,890
the way the city's lit up at night
allegedly inspires him, so...

724
00:46:38,990 --> 00:46:42,440
But that's OK,
because I'm going dancing with Paul.

725
00:46:42,500 --> 00:46:44,250
Where's Carol?

726
00:46:44,250 --> 00:46:47,370
uh...She's in bed with a bad oyster,

727
00:46:47,390 --> 00:46:48,770
so I'll see you guys later.

728
00:46:48,770 --> 00:46:50,770
Thanks for dinner, Daddy.

729
00:46:50,930 --> 00:46:52,930
Bye, sweetie.

730
00:46:54,900 --> 00:46:56,730
Where do you think
Gil goes every night?

731
00:46:56,730 --> 00:47:00,700
You heard her.
He walks, and gets ideas.

732
00:47:00,750 --> 00:47:02,830
- You sound skeptical.
- No.

733
00:47:02,830 --> 00:47:06,510
I've seen what he earns,
but sometimes I think he's got a...

734
00:47:06,510 --> 00:47:07,990
got a... part missing,

735
00:47:07,990 --> 00:47:09,990
and I didn't like his remark about

736
00:47:09,990 --> 00:47:12,210
Tea Party Republicans.
They are decent

737
00:47:12,220 --> 00:47:14,130
people trying to take back the country.

738
00:47:14,130 --> 00:47:16,130
They are not
crypto-fascist

739
00:47:16,130 --> 00:47:18,130
airhead zombies.
You hear him say that?

740
00:47:18,130 --> 00:47:20,790
Nevertheless, I don't think
your idea of having him followed

741
00:47:20,790 --> 00:47:23,070
- is very practical.
- No?

742
00:47:23,190 --> 00:47:24,930
I'd like to know where he goes every night.

743
00:47:24,930 --> 00:47:26,690
Well, we know one thing:

744
00:47:26,690 --> 00:47:28,450
he doesn't go dancing.

745
00:47:41,220 --> 00:47:43,420
Oh! Excuse me!

746
00:47:44,630 --> 00:47:47,410
- Is this gentleman bothering you?
- Hello, Gil!

747
00:47:47,410 --> 00:47:50,060
Hey! How are you?
I was hoping we'd see you here.

748
00:47:50,400 --> 00:47:52,680
- What a great party!
- Oh, good.

749
00:47:52,680 --> 00:47:54,680
- It's nice to see you here.
- Thank you.

750
00:47:54,680 --> 00:47:56,680
Oh, Delfine?

751
00:47:56,680 --> 00:47:59,280
- Gil, we'll catch up with you later, OK?
- Sure, sure.

752
00:47:59,280 --> 00:48:01,280
<i>Bon soir, Madame.</i>
(Good evening, Madame.)

753
00:48:01,280 --> 00:48:03,860
- What a surprise!
- It was just a total fluke.

754
00:48:03,860 --> 00:48:05,600
I was at Gertrude Stein's,

755
00:48:05,600 --> 00:48:07,860
she's almost finished with my novel,
and I run into this guy.

756
00:48:07,860 --> 00:48:10,200
Turns out he's Archibald MacLeish.
He says he's on his way over here,

757
00:48:10,240 --> 00:48:12,000
come on over. Oh, I'm not
going to crash the Fitzgeralds,

758
00:48:12,020 --> 00:48:14,830
but then he said you'd be here.
You and Pablo, and...

759
00:48:14,830 --> 00:48:16,440
Oh, Pablo's home.

760
00:48:16,440 --> 00:48:19,870
- We had a...bit of a quarrel.
- Oh no!

761
00:48:20,120 --> 00:48:23,750
- You look like you were having fun with Djuna Barnes, dancing.
- Oh, yeah!

762
00:48:23,750 --> 00:48:25,750
Wait. That was Djuna Barnes?

763
00:48:25,750 --> 00:48:28,290
- Yeah.
- Wow. No wonder she wanted to lead.

764
00:48:28,290 --> 00:48:32,100
Isn't this a wonderful
place to throw a party?

765
00:48:32,100 --> 00:48:35,570
- It's so great!
- Only the Fitzgeralds can do that!

766
00:48:35,640 --> 00:48:38,720
- I want to show you something. Come with me.
- OK.

767
00:48:40,530 --> 00:48:44,030
- So, what about your book?
- It's coming along. Yeah!

768
00:48:44,700 --> 00:48:46,980
Look at that!

769
00:48:46,980 --> 00:48:50,540
- Wow!
- It's from the turn of the century.

770
00:48:50,540 --> 00:48:53,810
Isn't it beautiful?
It's my favorite era.

771
00:48:53,990 --> 00:48:56,900
I love it so much.
Everything was so perfect.

772
00:48:56,900 --> 00:48:58,920
It's so nice to see you tonight.

773
00:48:58,920 --> 00:49:00,730
- I was hoping to...
- It's so nice to see you!

774
00:49:00,730 --> 00:49:03,080
<i>Voilà, ma petite Adriana!</i>
(There she is, my little Adriana!)

775
00:49:03,080 --> 00:49:07,850
Isn't this little Parisian
dream a moveable feast?

776
00:49:07,990 --> 00:49:10,160
Mark my words.
I'm going to steal you away

777
00:49:10,160 --> 00:49:13,160
from that fugitive from
Málaga one way or another.

778
00:49:13,160 --> 00:49:15,980
Between Belmonte and myself,
whom would you choose?

779
00:49:15,980 --> 00:49:17,590
<i>Vous êtes tous deux parfaits.</i>
(You are both perfect.)

780
00:49:17,590 --> 00:49:20,420
But he has more courage.
He faces death more often, and

781
00:49:20,420 --> 00:49:23,600
more directly, and if you chose him,
I'd be disappointed, but I'd understand.

782
00:49:23,600 --> 00:49:25,280
<i>Ella ha elegido Pablo.>
(She chose Pablo.)</i>

783
00:49:25,290 --> 00:49:27,820
Yes, she's chosen Picasso,
but Pablo thinks

784
00:49:27,820 --> 00:49:30,510
women are only to sleep
with or to paint.

785
00:49:30,730 --> 00:49:32,080
What about you?

786
00:49:32,080 --> 00:49:34,740
I think a woman is equal
to a man in courage.

787
00:49:34,740 --> 00:49:37,310
Have you ever shot
a charging lion?

788
00:49:37,630 --> 00:49:39,150
Never.

789
00:49:39,150 --> 00:49:41,480
Would you like to know
how that feels?

790
00:49:41,480 --> 00:49:43,490
- I don't think so.
- You ever hunted?

791
00:49:43,490 --> 00:49:44,890
- No.
- You?

792
00:49:44,890 --> 00:49:47,130
Only for bargains.

793
00:49:47,970 --> 00:49:50,690
<i>Tomémonos otra copita.</i>
(Let's take another drink.)

794
00:49:50,720 --> 00:49:53,760
You know, it's so loud,
I wonder if we can go some place

795
00:49:53,760 --> 00:49:57,870
- where we can hear ourselves think a little bit?
- Sure! Bye.

796
00:49:57,890 --> 00:50:00,000
Who wants a fight?

797
00:50:00,040 --> 00:50:03,410
Well, I hope it was nothing
serious with you and Pablo.

798
00:50:03,410 --> 00:50:06,080
He's moody and possessive.

799
00:50:06,080 --> 00:50:07,910
Artists are like children.

800
00:50:07,910 --> 00:50:11,150
Well, you certainly understand why
all these guys want to paint you,

801
00:50:11,150 --> 00:50:14,290
'cause you have just about
one of the best faces ever.

802
00:50:14,290 --> 00:50:17,360
- It's so interesting...
- Oh?

803
00:50:17,660 --> 00:50:21,790
- You're interesting, too, in a lost way.
- Lost?

804
00:50:22,570 --> 00:50:24,520
Well, I guess I am lost.

805
00:50:24,520 --> 00:50:26,520
Tell me more about your book.

806
00:50:26,670 --> 00:50:29,780
My book is kind of a...

807
00:50:29,910 --> 00:50:34,320
You know what?
I couldn't care less about my book tonight.

808
00:50:34,320 --> 00:50:36,550
I just want to walk around Paris with you.

809
00:50:36,550 --> 00:50:39,590
I keep forgetting you're just a tourist.

810
00:50:39,590 --> 00:50:41,650
That's putting it mildly.

811
00:50:41,650 --> 00:50:43,880
I can never decide whether

812
00:50:43,880 --> 00:50:47,500
Paris is more beautiful by day or by night.

813
00:50:47,500 --> 00:50:49,680
No, you can't.
You couldn't pick one. I mean,

814
00:50:49,710 --> 00:50:53,470
I can give you a checkmate
argument for each side.

815
00:50:53,470 --> 00:50:56,670
You know, I sometimes think,
"How's anyone gonna come up with a

816
00:50:56,670 --> 00:50:58,670
book, or a painting, or a

817
00:50:58,670 --> 00:51:02,160
symphony or a sculpture that can
compete with a great city?"

818
00:51:02,160 --> 00:51:04,660
You can't, 'cause, like,
you look around, every...

819
00:51:04,660 --> 00:51:08,530
every street, every boulevard
is its own special art form.

820
00:51:08,910 --> 00:51:11,890
And when you think that in the cold,

821
00:51:11,890 --> 00:51:16,220
violent, meaningless universe,
that Paris exists, these lights...

822
00:51:16,220 --> 00:51:20,290
I mean, come on, there's nothing
happening on Jupiter or Neptune,

823
00:51:20,290 --> 00:51:23,320
but from way out in space
you can see these lights,

824
00:51:23,320 --> 00:51:27,490
the cafés, people drinking, and singing...

825
00:51:27,490 --> 00:51:32,020
I mean, for all we know,
Paris is the hottest spot in the universe.

826
00:51:32,140 --> 00:51:34,240
- <i>Vous êtes un poète.</i>(You are a poet.)
- Aw, come on.

827
00:51:34,240 --> 00:51:39,630
It's just... You're very kind,
but I wouldn't call my babbling poetic.

828
00:51:39,700 --> 00:51:42,410
Although I was on a pretty good roll there.

829
00:51:42,820 --> 00:51:44,510
See anything you like?

830
00:51:44,510 --> 00:51:48,130
Yeah. I'm ashamed to admit
I'm attracted to all of them.

831
00:51:48,130 --> 00:51:51,440
I like cheap sexy.
That makes me shallow.

832
00:51:51,840 --> 00:51:55,370
When I was in Catholic school,
one weekend

833
00:51:55,370 --> 00:51:58,860
my roommate and I,
we paid a girl from Pigalle

834
00:51:58,860 --> 00:52:02,290
to come and teach us all her tricks.

835
00:52:02,310 --> 00:52:04,410
- Honestly?
- Yeah.

836
00:52:04,430 --> 00:52:06,430
Wow. That's...

837
00:52:06,990 --> 00:52:12,890
That's...That's...
I'm going to be thinking about that one.

838
00:52:19,790 --> 00:52:22,240
I love walking with you.

839
00:52:22,450 --> 00:52:25,510
- You look amazing.
- Thank you.

840
00:52:28,580 --> 00:52:31,310
God, is that who I think it is?

841
00:52:31,500 --> 00:52:34,040
What is she doing here,
staring into the water?

842
00:52:34,040 --> 00:52:36,470
Oh my God!

843
00:52:36,830 --> 00:52:38,830
Zelda, what are you doing?!

844
00:52:38,830 --> 00:52:41,400
- Please? I don't want to live!
- Stop!

845
00:52:41,400 --> 00:52:44,440
- What is it?
- Scott and that beautiful countess.

846
00:52:45,010 --> 00:52:47,200
They were-- It was so obvious
they were whispering about me,

847
00:52:47,240 --> 00:52:50,710
and the more they drank,
the more he fell in love with her!

848
00:52:50,710 --> 00:52:52,540
He...Scott loves only you.

849
00:52:52,540 --> 00:52:54,860
- I can tell you that with absolute certainty.
- No.

850
00:52:54,860 --> 00:52:57,550
- He's tired of me!
- You're wrong. You're wrong. I know.

851
00:52:57,980 --> 00:53:01,280
- How?
- Trust me. I know.

852
00:53:02,010 --> 00:53:04,720
- Sometimes you get a feel for people, and I get...
- My skin hurts!

853
00:53:04,720 --> 00:53:08,130
- What do you mean?
- I don't wanna...I hate the way I look!

854
00:53:08,130 --> 00:53:10,130
Don't do that!

855
00:53:11,390 --> 00:53:13,620
- Here. Take this.
- What is this?

856
00:53:13,620 --> 00:53:15,620
It's a Valium.
It'll make you feel better.

857
00:53:15,840 --> 00:53:18,050
- You carry medicine?
- No, not normally.

858
00:53:18,050 --> 00:53:19,900
It's just since I've been engaged to Inez,

859
00:53:19,900 --> 00:53:24,650
I've been having panic attacks,
but I'm sure they'll subside after the wedding.

860
00:53:24,650 --> 00:53:27,110
I've never heard of Valium.
What is this?

861
00:53:27,110 --> 00:53:30,630
It's the...pill of the future.

862
00:53:34,600 --> 00:53:37,180
You never said you were getting married.

863
00:53:37,180 --> 00:53:40,500
Yeah. You know,
it's still a....

864
00:53:40,500 --> 00:53:43,220
ways in the future.

865
00:53:43,490 --> 00:53:47,480
- Well, good luck with your book, and your wedding.
- Thank you.

866
00:53:47,620 --> 00:53:49,990
I think you'd like Inez.
She has a...

867
00:53:49,990 --> 00:53:52,530
has a very sharp sense of humor, and

868
00:53:52,530 --> 00:53:56,860
she's attractive. She doesn't say
that we agree on everything, but...

869
00:53:57,070 --> 00:53:59,110
But the important things.

870
00:53:59,110 --> 00:54:01,240
Yeah, or...actually,

871
00:54:01,240 --> 00:54:03,200
maybe the small things. The...

872
00:54:03,200 --> 00:54:06,750
Sometimes there's a little bit
of a disconnect with the big things.

873
00:54:06,750 --> 00:54:09,220
She wants to live in Malibu, and

874
00:54:09,220 --> 00:54:12,110
wants me to work in Hollywood, and....

875
00:54:12,700 --> 00:54:15,380
But I will say that we both like

876
00:54:15,880 --> 00:54:18,940
Indian food.
Not all Indian food, but the...

877
00:54:18,940 --> 00:54:21,090
you know...the pita bread.

878
00:54:21,090 --> 00:54:24,360
We both like pita bread.
I guess it's called naan.

879
00:54:25,710 --> 00:54:27,380
I should go.

880
00:54:27,770 --> 00:54:29,380
Pablo will be missing me.

881
00:54:29,380 --> 00:54:31,690
- Come on. I'll walk you home.
- No. No. No.

882
00:54:31,690 --> 00:54:34,000
Just finish your drink.
I live just around the corner.

883
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:38,410
- No. Come on. I'm not gonna...
- Well, I...I...prefer to be by myself for a while,

884
00:54:38,410 --> 00:54:42,420
but thank you for the evening.
Bye.

885
00:54:44,910 --> 00:54:47,800
<i>Monsieur? C'est un dommage.</i>
(Sir? It's a shame.)

886
00:54:47,800 --> 00:54:49,800
<i>C'est un dommage.</i>
(It's a shame.)

887
00:54:50,370 --> 00:54:52,530
We met, earlier tonight...

888
00:54:53,080 --> 00:54:54,870
At the party!

889
00:54:55,310 --> 00:54:56,870
<i>Dalí, sí?</i>
(Dalí, yes?)

890
00:54:56,870 --> 00:54:59,270
- Yes...
- Dalí!

891
00:54:59,270 --> 00:55:02,350
- I remember!
- Dalí. Ya.

892
00:55:02,620 --> 00:55:05,020
<i>Un bouteille de vin rouge!</i>
(A bottle of red wine!)

893
00:55:06,390 --> 00:55:09,310
It can't be...
Yeah....

894
00:55:09,910 --> 00:55:11,440
So?

895
00:55:12,130 --> 00:55:14,830
<i>Un autre verre pour monsieur, s'il vous plaît.</i>
(Another glass for this man, please.)

896
00:55:14,940 --> 00:55:17,650
I love the language!

897
00:55:17,650 --> 00:55:21,980
The French!
The waiters? No.

898
00:55:22,810 --> 00:55:26,400
You like the shape of the rhinoceros?

899
00:55:26,680 --> 00:55:29,300
The rhinoceros? Uh...

900
00:55:29,670 --> 00:55:32,260
Haven't really thought about it.

901
00:55:32,460 --> 00:55:36,820
I paint the rhinoceros.
I paint you.

902
00:55:36,860 --> 00:55:39,990
<i>Sí.</i> Your sad eyes.

903
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:44,570
Your big lips, melting over the hot sand,

904
00:55:44,600 --> 00:55:46,900
with one tear.

905
00:55:46,910 --> 00:55:51,530
Yes! And in your tear,
another face.

906
00:55:51,560 --> 00:55:54,140
The Christ's face!

907
00:55:54,290 --> 00:55:57,330
Yes, in the rhinoceros.

908
00:55:57,470 --> 00:56:00,500
Yeah. I mean, I probably do look sad. I'm in...

909
00:56:00,500 --> 00:56:03,830
a very perplexing situation.

910
00:56:04,720 --> 00:56:08,930
<>Diablo...Luis! Oye, Luis!
(Damn. Luis! Hey, Luis!)

911
00:56:09,120 --> 00:56:11,520
My friends.

912
00:56:11,990 --> 00:56:14,490
This... Señor Buñuel.

913
00:56:14,680 --> 00:56:18,500
- Buñuel?
- Sí. Buñuel...and...Mr. Man Ray.

914
00:56:18,690 --> 00:56:21,490
- Man Ray? My Gosh!
- How 'bout that?

915
00:56:21,490 --> 00:56:25,260
This is Pen-der. Pen-der.

916
00:56:25,550 --> 00:56:27,460
Pender!

