01:24:14,420 --> 01:24:16,740
You know, it seems like I'm
moving forward.

1361
01:24:16,740 --> 01:24:18,520
I mean, it just means
the world to me that you

1362
01:24:18,520 --> 01:24:20,640
- Hemingway read the chapters, too, and he thinks...
- He read it?

1363
01:24:20,640 --> 01:24:22,640
...he thinks it's going to be a fine book.

1364
01:24:22,640 --> 01:24:24,730
but he did have one plot suggestion.

1365
01:24:24,730 --> 01:24:25,960
What's the suggestion?

1366
01:24:25,960 --> 01:24:27,910
Well, he doesn't quite believe
that the protagonist

1367
01:24:27,930 --> 01:24:32,400
doesn't see that his fiancée is
having an affair right before his eyes.

1368
01:24:32,620 --> 01:24:35,930
- With?
- The other character. The pedantic one.

1369
01:24:41,770 --> 01:24:44,280
That's called denial.

1370
01:24:44,280 --> 01:24:46,280
Thank you.

1371
01:24:46,960 --> 01:24:48,520
You're crazy!

1372
01:24:48,520 --> 01:24:50,520
Paul and I?

1373
01:24:50,520 --> 01:24:53,260
Where did you get such an insane notion?

1374
01:24:53,260 --> 01:24:55,260
Where? From Ernest Hemingway.

1375
01:24:55,260 --> 01:24:58,100
He figured it out, and, guess what,
it makes perfect sense.

1376
01:24:58,100 --> 01:25:00,180
Gil, your brain tumor's acting up again.

1377
01:25:00,180 --> 01:25:02,630
- No. No!
- There's nothing crazy about Hemingway,

1378
01:25:02,630 --> 01:25:05,580
or Fitzgerald, or Gertrude Stein,
or Salvador Dalí!

1379
01:25:05,580 --> 01:25:08,060
Yeah, except that they've been dead for years!

1380
01:25:08,060 --> 01:25:09,990
No, no. The past is not dead.

1381
01:25:09,990 --> 01:25:12,710
Actually, it's not even past.
You know who said that?

1382
01:25:12,710 --> 01:25:14,860
Faulkner. And he was right.
And I met him, too.

1383
01:25:14,860 --> 01:25:16,380
I ran into him at a dinner party.

1384
01:25:16,380 --> 01:25:18,160
- You're a raving lunatic!
- No, I'm not.

1385
01:25:18,160 --> 01:25:20,480
- Yes, you are.
- No. I'm too trusting.

1386
01:25:20,480 --> 01:25:22,480
I'm jealous,
and I'm trusting.

1387
01:25:22,480 --> 01:25:24,060
It's cognitive dissonance.

1388
01:25:24,060 --> 01:25:25,300
- Scott Fitzgerald talked about it.
- Gil. Gil.

1389
01:25:25,300 --> 01:25:28,160
Inez, you can fool me,
but you cannot fool Hemingway.

1390
01:25:28,160 --> 01:25:31,010
- I know.
- Jesus Christ, I'm dealing with a madman here.

1391
01:25:31,010 --> 01:25:33,500
OK. Yes! I did.

1392
01:25:33,500 --> 01:25:36,090
I was with Paul for a few nights,

1393
01:25:36,090 --> 01:25:39,360
because he's romantic,
and he speaks French,

1394
01:25:39,360 --> 01:25:43,910
and you were always working, and maybe it's
the mystique of this corny city, but...

1395
01:25:43,910 --> 01:25:45,910
get over it, Gil.

1396
01:25:46,830 --> 01:25:49,150
You just put this in perspective
when we get home.

1397
01:25:49,460 --> 01:25:53,020
I'm not...I'm not going back.

1398
01:25:53,610 --> 01:25:57,190
- I'm sorry. What?
- I'm staying here, and it has nothing to do with,

1399
01:25:57,210 --> 01:25:59,800
you know, your romantic fling;
Paris is Paris.

1400
01:25:59,800 --> 01:26:02,140
Inez, you and I, it's obvious we're not...

1401
01:26:02,140 --> 01:26:04,630
I don't think we're right for each other.

1402
01:26:06,220 --> 01:26:07,860
What?

1403
01:26:08,550 --> 01:26:09,870
What are you saying?

1404
01:26:09,870 --> 01:26:12,590
What are you even talking about?

1405
01:26:14,940 --> 01:26:17,150
- You ready to go swimming?
- Hi!

1406
01:26:17,150 --> 01:26:18,770
We're breaking up.

1407
01:26:18,770 --> 01:26:20,980
- What?
- Yeah. Gil's moving to Paris.

1408
01:26:20,980 --> 01:26:22,980
- I knew it. I told you.
- What's going on?

1409
01:26:22,980 --> 01:26:25,700
No, no, I'm going to stay in Paris, but

1410
01:26:25,700 --> 01:26:27,220
just because we're...

1411
01:26:27,220 --> 01:26:30,010
If I'm unhappy, I'll move back.
But for the time being, yes.

1412
01:26:30,010 --> 01:26:32,640
W...W...With who?...
With who, Gil?

1413
01:26:32,640 --> 01:26:35,490
- No one, I...
- One of your crazy hallucinatory friends?

1414
01:26:35,520 --> 01:26:37,490
I mean, Mom's right about you.

1415
01:26:37,490 --> 01:26:39,380
You have this part missing.

1416
01:26:39,380 --> 01:26:40,760
Yeah, I said that first.

1417
01:26:40,760 --> 01:26:43,060
Anyone whose protagonist
makes a living

1418
01:26:43,060 --> 01:26:46,420
selling old cap pistols
and Joan Crawford cutout books...

1419
01:26:46,420 --> 01:26:49,100
- Honestly...
- Look, I'm not trying to be

1420
01:26:49,100 --> 01:26:51,880
a martyr, but I think
you'll be better off without me.

1421
01:26:51,880 --> 01:26:54,540
- I really do.
- But we would!

1422
01:26:54,540 --> 01:26:57,670
- I can't believe you're moving.
- Go ahead. Go ahead!

1423
01:26:57,670 --> 01:27:02,990
Walk the streets. Gush over the
Parisian light and the rooftops.

1424
01:27:02,990 --> 01:27:04,990
Goodbye, Inez.

1425
01:27:05,640 --> 01:27:07,980
- Say hi to Trotsky.
- Yeah.

1426
01:27:09,300 --> 01:27:12,820
- Unbelievable!
- You know, I had...

1427
01:27:12,820 --> 01:27:16,750
a private detective follow him.
I knew he was up to no good.

1428
01:27:16,750 --> 01:27:18,910
- You did?
- You bet I did.

1429
01:27:18,910 --> 01:27:20,930
He saw him get into a car
at midnight every night,

1430
01:27:20,930 --> 01:27:22,930
and he followed him very closely.

1431
01:27:23,210 --> 01:27:26,240
- And what happened?
- I don't know.

1432
01:27:26,240 --> 01:27:30,340
The detective agency says
the detective is missing.

1433
01:27:31,400 --> 01:27:32,660
<i>À qui dois-je l'honneur?</i>
(To whom do I owe the honor?)

1434
01:27:32,660 --> 01:27:35,130
<i>Je...Je suis perdu.</i>
(I...I'm lost.)

1435
01:27:35,130 --> 01:27:37,130
<i>J'ai detournée la mauvaise endroit.</i>
(I made a wrong turn.)

1436
01:27:37,130 --> 01:27:40,310
<i>Gardes! Gardes!</i>
(Guards! Guards!)

1437
01:27:40,670 --> 01:27:42,310
<i>Lui coupe la tête!</i>
(Off with his head!)

1438
01:27:42,520 --> 01:27:44,310
<i>Lui coupe la tête!</i>
(Off with his head!)

1439
01:28:51,320 --> 01:28:54,250
- Hey! Hi!
- Hey!

1440
01:28:55,430 --> 01:28:57,870
Wow! What...

1441
01:28:58,800 --> 01:29:01,000
Good to see you.

1442
01:29:01,000 --> 01:29:03,080
What are you doing here?

1443
01:29:03,080 --> 01:29:05,250
I'm returning from dinner with friends.

1444
01:29:05,250 --> 01:29:07,250
- Oh. OK.
- I live here.

1445
01:29:07,250 --> 01:29:10,310
And you? What are you doing here?

1446
01:29:10,830 --> 01:29:12,700
I was just out for a walk.

1447
01:29:12,700 --> 01:29:15,980
Yeah, I'm actually...I decided.
I'm moving to Paris.

1448
01:29:15,980 --> 01:29:19,590
- Really? Wow. I'm sure you will love it.
- Yeah.

1449
01:29:19,590 --> 01:29:22,490
- Yeah. You think so?
- Yeah.

1450
01:29:22,630 --> 01:29:24,830
You know, I thought about
you the other day.

1451
01:29:24,830 --> 01:29:26,620
- Really?
- Yeah, because

1452
01:29:26,620 --> 01:29:30,370
my boss got a whole
new album of Cole Porter songs.

1453
01:29:30,370 --> 01:29:32,670
That made you think about me?

1454
01:29:32,750 --> 01:29:35,640
I like to be thought of that way.

1455
01:29:35,640 --> 01:29:39,880
You're on your way home right now?

1456
01:29:40,420 --> 01:29:41,880
Yes.

1457
01:29:41,880 --> 01:29:46,100
Can I walk with you,
or, I'll buy you a cup of coffee?

1458
01:29:46,100 --> 01:29:49,110
Oh, OK, now it's starting to rain.

1459
01:29:50,250 --> 01:29:54,010
No, but that's OK.
I don't mind getting wet.

1460
01:29:54,570 --> 01:29:57,100
- Really?
- Yeah.

1461
01:29:57,420 --> 01:30:01,710
Actually, Paris is the most beautiful in the rain.

1462
01:30:01,740 --> 01:30:04,050
I feel that's what
I'm always saying.

1463
01:30:04,050 --> 01:30:06,600
I couldn't agree more with you.

1464
01:30:06,600 --> 01:30:09,910
Yes, it is more beautiful.

1465
01:30:09,910 --> 01:30:12,710
By the way, my name is Gabrielle.

1466
01:30:12,710 --> 01:30:15,060
- Gil.
- Nice to meet you.
